{"title_page": "UNSW Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name           = UNSW Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| caption        = \n| motto          = \n| motto_lang     = \n| motto_eng      = \n| former_names   = Faculty of Arts\n| established    = 1960\n| type           = \n| parent         = [[University of New South Wales]]\n| affiliation    = \n| city           = Kensington\n| state          = New South Wales\n| country        = Australia\n| coordinates    = \n| dean           = Professor Susan Dodds\n| academic_staff = 280\n| students       = 6,692\n| undergrad      = 4,863\n| postgrad       = \n| doctoral       = \n| alumni         = 54,000\n| website        = {{url|https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/}}\n| logo           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences''' is a constituent body of the [[University of New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. Initially established as the Faculty of Arts in 1960 under founding Dean, Professor Morven Brown, it was renamed the Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences in 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.recordkeeping.unsw.edu.au/historicalresources/onlineexhibitions/unitimelineexhibition/1960s.html#1960|title=1960s|first=UNSW Archives|last=Timeline|date=28 August 2013|website=www.recordkeeping.unsw.edu.au|accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIt comprises four schools: Arts and Media, Education, Humanities and Languages, and Social Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/schools-centres/schools/|title=Schools - Arts & Social Sciences - UNSW Australia|website=UNSW|accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref> The Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences offers over 45 undergraduate degree programs and 27 postgraduate coursework programs. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/about-us/faculty/|title= \"About Us - Arts & Social Sciences - UNSW Australia\" |publisher=UNSW|access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the university's Kensington campus, the faculty occupies the Morven Brown and Robert Webster buildings, as well as parts of the John Goodsell Building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/about-us/faculty/location/|title=Location - Arts & Social Sciences - UNSW Australia|website=UNSW|accessdate=10 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Juvenilia Press]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/ UNSW Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences website]\n\n{{University of New South Wales}}\n\n{{coord missing|New South Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Faculties of the University of New South Wales|Arts, Faculty of]]\n[[Category:Art schools in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name           = UNSW Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| image_alt      = \n| caption        = \n| motto          = \n| motto_lang     = \n| motto_eng      = \n| former_names   = Faculty of Arts\n| established    = 1960\n| type           = \n| parent         = [[University of New South Wales]]\n| affiliation    = \n| city           = Sydney\n| state          = New South Wales\n| country        = Australia\n| coordinates    = \n| dean           = Professor Susan Dodds\n| academic_staff = 280\n| students       = 6,692\n| undergrad      = 4,863\n| postgrad       = \n| doctoral       = \n| alumni         = 54,000\n| website        = {{url|https://www.arts.unsw.edu.au/}}\n| logo           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences''' is a constituent body of the [[University of New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. Initially established as the Faculty of Arts in 1960 under founding Dean, Professor Morven Brown, it was renamed the Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences in 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.recordkeeping.unsw.edu.au/historicalresources/onlineexhibitions/unitimelineexhibition/1960s.html#1960|title=1960s|first=UNSW Archives|last=Timeline|date=28 August 2013|website=www.recordkeeping.unsw.edu.au|